        <h1>LeetCode 3751: Total Waviness of Numbers in Range I (C++)</h1>
        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                An integer is called wavy if, for every adjacent pair of digits, they are either all alternately greater
                and less than each other. Given two numbers num1 and num2, return the sum of the count of wavy numbers
                for each number in the range [num1, num2]. A digit is considered a peak if it is greater than both
                neighbors, or a valley if it is less than both neighbors.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: num1 = 1, num2 = 3<br>
                Output: 0<br>
                Explanation: Single digit numbers have no peaks or valleys. 1, 2, and 3 are all single digits, so the
                answer is 0.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    int totalWaviness(int num1, int num2) {
        int ans = 0;
        for (int num = num1; num &lt;= num2; num++) {
            string str = to_string(num);
            for (int pos = 1; pos &lt; (int)str.size() - 1; pos++) {
                // check whether current digit forms a peak or valley
                if ((str[pos] &gt; str[pos - 1] &amp;&amp; str[pos] &gt; str[pos + 1]) ||
                    (str[pos] &lt; str[pos - 1] &amp;&amp; str[pos] &lt; str[pos + 1])) {
                    ans++;
                }
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};</code></pre>
